## detection

two layers caught this attack — the splunk rule and the automated triage tool.

**layer 1 — splunk detection rule (T1110.001)**

```
index=main sourcetype=linux_secure "Failed password"
| stats count by host
| where count > 5
```

runs every 5 minutes. fired within the first 2 minutes of the attack starting.

**layer 2 — auto_triage.py**

once the alert fired, auto_triage.py picked it up on its next 60-second poll, ran the SPL query, extracted the source IP, queried abuseipdb for threat intelligence, calculated a risk score, and logged a structured case file automatically.

```
CASE-20260615-001  |  SSH Brute Force
Technique : T1110.001
Severity  : High
Source IP : 192.168.1.95
Abuse Score: 0%  |  Country: US  |  ISP: Local Network
IP Risk   : LOW
Decision  : NEEDS_REVIEW
Action    : IP appears clean in threat intel but alert threshold was
            crossed. check if this is an internal scanner, authorized
            pen test, or misconfigured service.
```

note: LOW risk and NEEDS_REVIEW is the correct decision for a homelab — the source IP is a private local address so abuseipdb has no reports on it. in a real environment an external IP doing this would score much higher and trigger TRUE_POSITIVE.

